---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
import OpportunityCard from '@/components/OpportunityCard.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="The Protein Works vs Myprotein — PDP Competitor Analysis">

  <section class="report-intro">
    <h1 class="report-h1">Competitor Analysis: The Protein Works vs Myprotein</h1>
    <p class="report-meta">Product Detail Page &mdash; Analysed 8 June 2026</p>
    <p class="report-summary">
      The Protein Works positions itself as a science-led, flavour-obsessed protein brand targeting
      serious fitness consumers who want transparency and range. Their Whey Protein 360 PDP was
      compared against Myprotein's Impact Whey Protein PDP — the closest equivalent entry-level
      whey product. Three patterns stood out where TPW's PDP earns conversion advantages Myprotein's
      current PDP doesn't replicate: an in-page product tier comparison table that drives informed
      upsell, a rating distribution breakdown that builds trust through transparency, and customer
      quotes embedded directly in cross-sell product cards.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="opportunities-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Opportunities for Myprotein</h2>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="In-page product tier comparison table"
      competitor="The Protein Works"
      viewport="Desktop"
      categories="conversion,discovery"
      opportunityId="tier-comparison-table"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Below the main product content, TPW includes a section titled "Worth the upgrade? 100 per cent."
        which presents a structured side-by-side table comparing their three Whey Protein 360 tiers
        (BLACK, GOLD, PLATINUM) across ~10 nutritional attributes: price per serving, protein per
        serving, number of protein sources, calories, vitamins &amp; minerals, approved health benefits,
        flavour count, premium flavours, digestive enzymes, and GLP-1 compatibility. Each tier is
        labelled with a purchase intent framing ("Best Price", "Best Value", "Best Rated") and uses
        check/cross marks for boolean attributes. The table sits on a dark background and links
        directly to each tier's product page.
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/the-protein-works-vs-myprotein-pdp-2026-06-08/tpw-tier-comparison-detail.png" alt="TPW in-page product tier comparison table showing BLACK, GOLD and PLATINUM tiers side by side" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A user landing on the entry-level whey page is often mid-decision — they know they want whey
        protein but haven't committed to a tier or brand. Showing the upgrade comparison on the same
        page captures that indecision in favour of a higher-value product without requiring navigation.
        The framing ("Best Price" vs "Best Value" vs "Best Rated") is deliberately chosen: it doesn't
        make the entry tier look inferior, it just makes the middle tier feel obviously worth the small
        price increase. This is a well-established CRO pattern — exposing tiered options at the point
        of consideration increases average order value and reduces cross-session drop-off.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein sells Impact Whey, Impact Whey Advanced, and THE Whey as a de facto tier stack, but
        the PDP makes no attempt to surface this. A user on the Impact Whey page has no in-page prompt
        to consider Impact Whey Advanced (more protein, added BCAAs) without navigating elsewhere.
        Adding a compact "Compare the range" module — even as a 2-column card comparison rather than
        a full table — to the Impact Whey PDP could intercept undecided shoppers and move them toward
        a higher-margin product. The labelling approach ("Best Value", "Most Popular") is worth
        borrowing directly.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Rating distribution breakdown with percentage bars"
      competitor="The Protein Works"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="trust"
      opportunityId="rating-breakdown-bars"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        In the reviews section, TPW displays a full percentage distribution per star rating alongside
        the aggregate score. Each rating tier (1–5 stars) has a horizontal bar and an explicit
        percentage: 5★ 40%, 4★ 4%, 3★ 8%, 2★ 11%, 1★ 37%. Crucially, the distribution is shown
        even when it is unflattering — 37% of reviews are 1-star on this particular product, and
        they make no attempt to hide or truncate this.
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/the-protein-works-vs-myprotein-pdp-2026-06-08/tpw-reviews-breakdown-detail.png" alt="TPW rating distribution breakdown showing percentage bars per star rating" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Showing the full distribution, including negative skews, is paradoxically a trust signal.
        Users who see only an aggregate score are left to wonder whether it reflects a genuine spread
        or an artificially managed set. A visible distribution lets customers self-qualify: a user
        who filters for 1-star reviews to understand the failure modes is more informed and therefore
        less likely to return the product. Hiding the distribution invites suspicion; showing it
        honestly reduces it.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein shows an aggregate rating and total review count (4.4 stars, 210k+ reviews) but
        does not surface a star-by-star percentage breakdown on the PDP. With 210,000+ reviews,
        Myprotein has far more data to make this credible and useful than TPW does. A distribution
        bar chart in the reviews section — especially showing the dominant 4- and 5-star clusters
        that Impact Whey likely has — would give users the transparency signal without the risk
        of undermining confidence.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Customer quote embedded in cross-sell product cards"
      competitor="The Protein Works"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="trust,conversion"
      opportunityId="crosssell-customer-quotes"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        In the "Customers Also Viewed" section, each product card includes a short pulled customer
        quote alongside the standard rating, price, and CTA. Example: "These are genuinely the best
        protein bars I've ever tasted! I went for the peanut punk... — DanStan". The quote appears
        between the star rating and the price, in small italic text. Each card also has two CTAs:
        a secondary "Quick Buy" and a primary "Product Details".
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/the-protein-works-vs-myprotein-pdp-2026-06-08/tpw-crosssell-detail.png" alt="TPW cross-sell product cards showing embedded customer quotes alongside ratings and CTAs" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Cross-sell carousels typically have low engagement because they feel transactional — just
        another product grid. A customer quote adds a human signal that differentiates each product
        beyond its image and price. The quote doesn't need to be the best review ever written; its
        function is to give the user a lived-experience anchor at the moment of consideration, before
        they've committed to clicking through. It also reinforces that these products have been
        bought and validated by real customers, not just algorithmically surfaced.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's "Recommended for you" carousel shows product images, names, discounted pricing,
        and a Quick Buy button — but no social proof on the card itself. Given that Myprotein has
        one of the largest review datasets in the UK sports nutrition market, pulling a short
        highlighted review into each cross-sell card is feasible and would make the carousel feel
        less generic. Even showing a review snippet for the top-reviewed variant of each product
        would meaningfully increase the perceived confidence of clicking through.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Areas Where Myprotein Already Leads</h2>
    <p>
      Myprotein's Impact Whey PDP has a meaningfully larger review base (210,000+ vs TPW's 135 on
      this specific product), which gives far greater social proof weight at a glance. Myprotein
      also surfaces a Trustpilot aggregate score on the PDP, as does TPW — so this is a draw, not
      a gap. Myprotein's flavour range for Impact Whey is substantially wider (50+ flavours) than
      TPW's 5, which is a genuine product-level advantage that the PDP communicates through its
      flavour selector. The size selector on Myprotein's PDP is also standard and clear. TPW's
      per-serving price display on size options (£0.40–£0.55 per shake) is the one area where
      their size selector goes further than Myprotein's — but this is a marginal gap compared to
      the three opportunities above.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Competitor Context</h2>
    <p>
      The Protein Works is a UK-based sports nutrition brand founded in 2012 that has built its
      identity around flavour innovation, nutritional transparency, and a tiered product architecture
      (BLACK / GOLD / PLATINUM). Their audience skews toward gym-regular consumers who research
      before buying and value detailed ingredient breakdowns. Unlike Myprotein, which competes on
      scale and accessibility, TPW positions itself as a considered purchase. Their PDP reflects this:
      it is content-heavy, narrative-driven, and designed to justify a buying decision rather than
      simply present product information. This context explains why the tier comparison table and
      rating transparency patterns exist — they serve a more deliberative shopper, not an impulse buyer.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="screenshots-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Page Screenshots</h2>
    <div class="screenshot-grid">
      <div class="screenshot-col">
        <p class="screenshot-label">The Protein Works — Desktop</p>
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/the-protein-works-vs-myprotein-pdp-2026-06-08/tpw-full-desktop.png" alt="The Protein Works Whey Protein 360 PDP full page desktop screenshot" />
      </div>
      <div class="screenshot-col">
        <p class="screenshot-label">Myprotein — Desktop</p>
        <img src="/assets/reports/competitors/the-protein-works-vs-myprotein-pdp-2026-06-08/myprotein-full-desktop.png" alt="Myprotein Impact Whey Protein PDP full page desktop screenshot" />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style>
  .report-intro { margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .report-h1 { font-size: 26px; font-weight: 800; color: var(--color-text-heading); line-height: 1.25; margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .report-meta { font-size: 13px; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.65; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .report-summary { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); max-width: 680px; }
  .opportunities-section { margin-bottom: 48px; }
  .section-heading { font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-heading); margin-bottom: 20px; padding-bottom: 10px; border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.1); }
  .prose-section { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  .prose-section p { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); }
  .screenshot-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; }
  .screenshot-col img { width: 100%; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid rgba(0,57,66,0.08); display: block; margin-top: 8px; }
  .screenshot-label { font-size: 12px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.55; margin: 0; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; }
  .screenshots-section { margin-top: 48px; }
</style>
